Group by
--------

It is used to group rows having the same values
and apply aggregate functions on each group.

1.Every non-aggregated column must be in GROUP BY
-------------------------------------------------
SELECT name, department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;

👉 ❌ Problem:

AVG(salary) → aggregated ✅
department → grouped ✅
name → ❌ not aggregated and not grouped

✅ Correct Query

SELECT department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY department;

✅ OR include all non-aggregated columns
SELECT name, department, AVG(salary)
FROM employees
GROUP BY name, department

------------
Simple Logic
-------------
👉 After GROUP BY, rows are grouped into one row per group

So:

Aggregated columns     →  summarized (AVG, SUM, etc.)
Non-aggregated columns →  must define the group



-----------------------------------
2. WHERE vs HAVING (with GROUP BY)
------------------------------------
Clause	Used For
WHERE	Filters rows before grouping
HAVING	Filters groups after grouping

FROM → WHERE → GROUP BY → HAVING → SELECT













